{"type":"message","id":"34f77bbd","parentId":"bc823f8a","timestamp":"2026-04-16T03:27:15.892Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is suggesting installing a Chrome extension to let VibeSurf control the host machine's Chrome browser instead of running Chrome inside the Docker container. This is actually a good idea - VibeSurf does support this through a Chrome extension that can connect to a remote browser instance.\n\nLet me check how VibeSurf's Chrome extension works - it should be able to connect to a Chrome instance running on the host machine (outside Docker), which would bypass the Docker memory constraints entirely.\n\nFrom the VibeSurf docs, there's usually a way to connect to a remote browser via CDP (Chrome DevTools Protocol). The extension runs in Chrome and can be configured to connect to a specific CDP endpoint.\n\n\nSo the Chrome extension on the host machine needs to either be running in debug mode with an open port, or connect to VibeSurf's server endpoint to establish the connection between them. I should look into what configuration options VibeSurf exposes for this remote browser setup."},{"type":"text","text":"这是个好思路！VibeSurf 有个 Chrome 扩展可以接管宿主机浏览器，不走容器里的 Chrome。\n\n扩展装好后，宿主机 Chrome 开调试模式，扩展连接到 VibeSurf，就能绕过 Docker 内存限制了。\n\n让我看一下 VibeSurf 的扩展配置方法：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ozmv3tw2xc36_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"curl -s --max-time 5 \"http://127.0.0.1:9335/api/tool/search?keyword=chrome\" 2>/dev/null | head -50","timeout":8}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776310024234,"responseId":"062f8a08c54afe69e549bffefdf993b6"}}
